1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,000
Traditional DNS tells a workload where a service is.
It does not decide whether that workload should reach it.

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,000
Name-Based Secure Routing adds identity, policy,
and short-lived authorization to that route.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:19,000
A client proves its workload identity to the NBSR control plane.
The control plane asks an OPA default-deny policy.

4
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:27,000
The control plane alone holds the private ticket-signing key.
When allowed, it creates a short-lived Ed25519 routing ticket.

5
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:35,000
The verifier receives only the public key. Envoy uses external authorization
and a fixed allowlisted route to the private payments service.

6
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:43,000
The client cannot connect to that backend directly.
All five Docker Compose services are ready.

7
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:54,000
The allowed workload resolves payments.internal
and reaches the service through Envoy.

8
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:05,000
The denied identity receives no route.
An unknown service is also denied by default.

9
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:17,000
A missing ticket is rejected.
Changing real decoded signature bytes is also rejected.

10
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:29,000
An automated regression test protects the tamper case.
The ticket cannot escalate its method or path.

11
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:42,000
The client cannot connect directly to the payments backend,
proving real network isolation.

12
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:55,000
The short-lived ticket expires and is rejected.
All eight real mandatory scenarios pass.

13
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:05,000
Tickets bind workload, service, method, path,
gateway audience, and expiration.

14
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:15,000
Envoy fails closed. Clients cannot choose an upstream,
and the backend has no published port.

15
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:24,000
Humans directed the concept, architecture, security requirements,
technology, scope, fail-closed criteria, testing, and submission decisions.

16
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:33,000
GPT-5.6 and Codex accelerated the FastAPI services, OPA and Envoy integration,
Docker and Kubernetes resources, tests, documentation, live validation,
and correction of the Base64 URL tamper-test flaw.

17
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:40,000
Compose was validated live. Kubernetes resources passed
offline validation, but live kind was not tested.

18
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:48,000
This is a validated prototype, not intended for production,
and it does not replace DNS. Identity and policy decide the temporary route.
The public repository is available on GitHub.
